  ## The Problem [\#](https://wicksipedia.com/blog/speeding-up-zsh-startup/\#the-problem)
  
  My terminal was slow. Really slow. Every time I opened a new shell, there was a noticeable lag before my prompt appeared. Admittedly this was a papercut, but it made me feel like my laptop was slowing down. I donŌĆÖt really want to upgrade right now, and I donŌĆÖt really want to go scorched earth and wipe my machine to start again to get a fresh, fast terminal. So I decided to optimize my existing setup.
  
  I jumped straight into fix-it mode. LetŌĆÖs start with `zoxide`, that must slow down things, right? So I disabled it, which promptly broke tab completion with errors like `__zoxide_z_complete: command not found`. Great, now I have broken tab completion _and_ a slow terminal. Fantastic.
  
  I fell into the classic trap of ŌĆ£ready, fire, aimŌĆØ. I made changes without measuring first.
  
  So I needed to do what I shouldŌĆÖve from the start, I added profiling to figure out where all that time was actually going. ­¤ż”
  
  ```
  # Add to the top of ~/.zshrc
  zmodload zsh/zprof
  
  # Add to the bottom
  zprofCopy
  ```
  
  As usual, the results were not what I expected.
  
  ## The Diagnosis [\#](https://wicksipedia.com/blog/speeding-up-zsh-startup/\#the-diagnosis)
  
  **Startup time: 640ms** ­¤Éī
  
  HereŌĆÖs what `zprof` revealed:
  
  | Function | Time (ms) | % of Total | Issue |
  | --- | --- | --- | --- |
  | `compinit` | 444 | 78.87% | **Called twice!** |
  | `compdump` | 181 | 32.20% | Writing completion cache |
  | `compdef` | 123 | 21.78% | 1,633 calls! |
  | `antigen` | 317 | 56.32% | Slow plugin manager |
  | `_omz_source` | 53 | 9.33% | Loading Oh-My-Zsh plugins |
  
  ThatŌĆÖs nice, but what does it actually mean? I had no idea what `compinit` or `compdef` were doing, and I had no idea why they were taking so long. I just knew that `zoxide` was the last thing I added, so it must be the problem, right?
  
  ## A Different Kind of Pair Programming [\#](https://wicksipedia.com/blog/speeding-up-zsh-startup/\#a-different-kind-of-pair-programming)
  
  I usually use GitHub Copilot for my day-to-day coding, but this week I decided to try out Claude Code for this optimization problem. The difference was notable.
  
  I pasted my `zprof` output into Claude and asked it to analyze the results. Within seconds, it identified the major culprits, and `zoxide` wasnŌĆÖt one of them.
  
  1. `compinit` was being called twiceŌĆöonce by Antigen, once by Oh-My-Zsh
  2. The plugin manager itself was eating 300ms+
  3. I had previously put in a quick fix for some plugins not working, and the full Oh-My-Zsh was loading when I only needed a handful of features
  4. I was loading a built in and external fzf plugin
  
  > Two minutes with `zprof` and a dash of AI would have saved me 20 minutes of wrong guesses. Measure first, tinker second.
  
  It suggested migrating from Antigen to Zinit. Ironically, IŌĆÖd tried Zinit a few years ago when I first set up [my terminal with Antigen](https://wicksipedia.com/blog/terminal-setup) but couldnŌĆÖt get it configured quite right so I parked it. Now with the power of AI, this would be different.
  
  HereŌĆÖs what made it valuable: **this wasnŌĆÖt just handing off the problem**. I asked questions throughout:
  
  - ŌĆ£Why is compinit being called twice?ŌĆØ
  - ŌĆ£WhatŌĆÖs the difference between these fzf plugins?ŌĆØ
  - ŌĆ£Can we keep the OMZ git plugin features I use?ŌĆØ
  
  We debugged the ZLE warnings together, and I understood each change we made. It felt more like pair programming than autocomplete ŌĆö and I ended up with a configuration I still understand.
  
  ## What Actually Worked [\#](https://wicksipedia.com/blog/speeding-up-zsh-startup/\#what-actually-worked)
  
  ### Step 1: Replace Antigen with Zinit [\#](https://wicksipedia.com/blog/speeding-up-zsh-startup/\#step-1-replace-antigen-with-zinit)
  
  Antigen is convenient but slow. [Zinit](https://github.com/zdharma-continuum/zinit) is a modern, faster alternative. This was a great suggestion from Claude, and it did a great job of converting my setup in a couple of minutes with only a few back-and-forths to fix edge cases.
  
  ```
  # Zinit installation (faster than antigen)
  ZINIT_HOME="${XDG_DATA_HOME:-${HOME}/.local/share}/zinit/zinit.git"
  [ ! -d $ZINIT_HOME ] && mkdir -p "$(dirname $ZINIT_HOME)"
  [ ! -d $ZINIT_HOME/.git ] && git clone https://github.com/zdharma-continuum/zinit.git "$ZINIT_HOME"
  source "${ZINIT_HOME}/zinit.zsh"Copy
  ```
  
  **Savings: ~200ms**
  
  ### Step 2: Load Only What You Need from Oh-My-Zsh [\#](https://wicksipedia.com/blog/speeding-up-zsh-startup/\#step-2-load-only-what-you-need-from-oh-my-zsh)
  
  Instead of loading the entire Oh-My-Zsh framework, I cherry-picked just the libraries and plugins I actually use. I had a list of plugins at the top of my `~/.zshrc` that I wanted to keep, so I made sure to include those. I wasnŌĆÖt aware that I had added a call in the prompt that caused the entire framework to load.
  
  ```
  # Load OMZ libs we need (not the whole thing)
  zinit snippet OMZL::git.zsh
  zinit snippet OMZL::theme-and-appearance.zsh
  zinit snippet OMZL::async_prompt.zsh  # Required by git plugin
  
  # Load OMZ plugins
  zinit snippet OMZP::git
  zinit snippet OMZP::brew
  zinit snippet OMZP::direnv
  zinit snippet OMZP::eza
  # Removed OMZP::fzf - using fzf-tab insteadCopy
  ```
  
  This eliminated the overhead of loading unused OMZ plugins and prevented the double `compinit` call.
  
  **Savings: ~150ms**
  
  ### Step 3: Loading 3rd Party Plugins [\#](https://wicksipedia.com/blog/speeding-up-zsh-startup/\#step-3-loading-3rd-party-plugins)
  
  ```
  # Fast syntax highlighting and autosuggestions
  zinit light zsh-users/zsh-syntax-highlighting
  zinit light zsh-users/zsh-autosuggestions
  
  # fzf-tab for better tab completion
  zinit light Aloxaf/fzf-tab
  # Don't load fzf-tab-source - it has bugs and we don't need itCopy
  ```
  
  **Key learning**: The OMZP::fzf plugin was causing harmless but annoying ZLE warnings. Since weŌĆÖre using the superior `fzf-tab` plugin, we donŌĆÖt need it.
  
  **Savings: ~50ms + eliminated warnings**
  
  ### Step 4: Load Completions Once [\#](https://wicksipedia.com/blog/speeding-up-zsh-startup/\#step-4-load-completions-once)
  
  Instead of letting multiple plugins call `compinit`, do it once explicitly:
  
  ```
  # Load completions efficiently
  autoload -Uz compinit
  compinitCopy
  ```
  
  **Savings: ~180ms (from eliminating duplicate call)**
  
  ### Step 5: Initialize Tools Properly [\#](https://wicksipedia.com/blog/speeding-up-zsh-startup/\#step-5-initialize-tools-properly)
  
  Re-enable zoxide (it wasnŌĆÖt the problem after all!):
  
  ```
  # Initialize tools
  eval "$(starship init zsh)"
  eval "$(fnm env --use-on-cd --shell zsh --version-file-strategy=recursive)"
  eval "$(zoxide init zsh)"Copy
  ```
  
  ## The Results [\#](https://wicksipedia.com/blog/speeding-up-zsh-startup/\#the-results)
  
  **New startup time: 120ms** ­¤ÜĆ
  
  | Metric | Before | After | Improvement |
  | --- | --- | --- | --- |
  | Plugin manager | Antigen (slow) | Zinit (fast) | Ō£ģ Upgraded |
  | ZLE Warnings | Multiple | None | Ō£ģ Fixed |
  | `compinit` calls | 2 | 1 | Ō£ģ Fixed |
  | Startup time | 640ms | 120ms | **81% faster** |
  
