  > does using `zcompile` actually improve performance?
  
  Yes, but very little.
  
  When I was benchmarking zcompile for powerlevel10k startup, the effect size was around 2ms. Powerelvel10k amounts to >70% of zsh code sourced by zsh4humans, and it's already compiled by powerlevel10k itself, so zcompile in zsh4humans has virtually no visible effect.
  
  I kept it there for two reasons. The first is that it'll help a little bit if you source more plugins. However my main goal was to curtail arguments that some plugin manager can do the same job faster. It's much easier for users to understand a simple claim that no plugin manager can achieve faster zsh startup compared to zsh4humans. The alternative statement -- some plugin managers can do it a bit faster but you won't notice it -- is too subtle to understand the implications of.
  
  > `zsh -i -c exit`
  
  While timing this command can tell you _something_, note that it's not the right metric to optimize for if you want to get fast zsh startup. Some snake oil peddlers might try to convince you otherwise but it's easy to show that the timing of `zsh -i -c exit` can be 10 times lower or 10 times higher than the real latency that you care about.
  
