  > Would you recommend I stop using zsh-defer in those places?
  
  Yes, absolutely.
  
  My high-level advice is to only add extra stuff to your configuration if it actually helps. Does `zsh-defer` do anything useful that you can detect? By that I don't mean the timing of `zsh -ic ''` (which is meaningless) but something you can detect with your own human senses.
  
  While `zsh-defer` is not doing anything good in your config, it's doing quite a bit of harm. For example, if you type fast enough to keep zle busy, you'll execute command(s) without environment from direnv. When you do get environment from direnv, the message saying so may be missing entirely. (Flags `-1 and -2` don't help because zle cannot print to console willy-nilly.)
  
  Note that zsh-defer for direnv in your config is applied only to `eval` but not to the call to `direnv hook`, which takes 99.9% of direnv initialization time. So it's not even reducing the irrelevant metric of `zsh -ic ''`.
  
  There are similar issues with everything else that's deferred in your config. I suppose setting `DISPLAY` isn't an optional thing and you probably want it to be done before you start executing commands? It shouldn't be deferred then.
  
  A few tips:
  
  1. Use `direnv hook zsh` instead of `direnv hook $SHELL`. If `$SHELL` is `zsh`, you are lucky. If your login shell happens to be `bash`, `direnv hook $SHELL` will result in errors as you'll try to initialize direnv using its integration code for bash.
  2. Make sure to use `$TTY` instead of `$(tty)` when initializing `GPG_TTY`. It's 1000+ times faster and doesn't break when using instant prompt.
  3. Are you sure you want `stty -ixon` and not `setopt no_flow_control`? If you do the latter, `ctrl-s` and `ctrl-q` won't do anything in zle and can be bound to anything you like. At the same time you retain the ability to pause terminal output with `ctrl-s` when some program starts spewing out logs with the speed of light (resume with `ctrl-q`). If you run `stty -ixon`, the effect on zle is the same but you lose the ability to pause/resume terminal output.
  
