  Yup, tmux is really nice for organizing lots of persistent terminal sessions, and it especially shines when SSHing to remote servers, because then even if there's a disconnection, when you connect again you get back the exact terminal state (including previous command output etc.).
  
  And if we're getting into terminal setups and Unix porn, here's a couple of other recommendations:
  
  - [kitty](https://github.com/kovidgoyal/kitty) is a great terminal emulator. Looking at your public dotfiles I see you tried alacritty, but from my experience kitty is much better (also GPU accelerated) and the author is much more responsive.
  - I don't know if you often run commands in multiple machines, but I do and I find it really helpful to be able to search the history from all machines. I use a custom tool in I built for that in golang which is also integrated with fzf but has some improvements like support for multiline commands, storing alias expansions (so if you change aliases in the future you can still search your history with the real commands), ipython integration, syntax highlighted command previews, computing command stats (so you can be data driven when you define aliases :), and showing the context of the command (commands executed before/after). I haven't published it yet (wanted to polish it more before doing so), but I can share it with you if you're interested. There's also [zsh-histdb](https://github.com/larkery/zsh-histdb) which looks good, but I haven't tested it.
  
