  I've tried pretty much all terminals out there (had to, due to people filing bugs). Alacritty is a massive disappointment -- no features to speak of and slower than almost everything else, despite their claims. Kitty is decent -- only slightly buggier than VTE-based terminals and not slow. VTE-based terminal (e.g., GNOME Terminal or Tilix) are the best IMO. The least buggy and with the smoothest rendering. If you try GNOME Terminal or Tilix and forget the hype that Kitty enjoys, you'll likely notice that rendering is more pleasant. It's especially noticeable when you enable instant prompt in p10k. I wasn't able to detect any difference in performance between Kitty and VTE in applications I care about, neither subjectively nor with benchmarks. The difference in rendering smoothness when using p10k is noticeable with naked eyes.
  
  That said, Kitty is alright. It's better than most terminals.
  
  As for history, I write history to a separate file on every machine and commit all these files to a private git repo. All these files are available on every machine, so I have a shared history everywhere.
  
  The features of zsh-histdb you describe sound pretty cool and might make it popular if you release it. It seems like your workflow is quite different from mine though. I use few aliases and almost never create or change them, so many features that are important to you aren't important to me. I much prefer to use history to recall often-used commands than to define an alias. FWIW, I also have syntax highlighting in history.
  
